6. Write a recursive descent parser for the grammar:

S → (L) | a

L → L , S | S



Here is the **simplest possible recursive-descent parser** for your grammar, assuming **input contains NO SPACES**.

---

# ✅ Grammar After Removing Left Recursion

```
S  → ( L ) | a
L  → S L'
L' → , S L' | ε
```

---

# ✅ **C Implementation (NO SPACES, only chars like a,(,),,)**

✔ Minimal
✔ Clean
✔ Direct grammar implementation
✔ Only checks VALID / INVALID

---

# ✅ **FINAL C PROGRAM**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

char input[100];
int pos = 0;

char get() {
    return input[pos];
}

void advance() {
    pos++;
}

void error() {
    printf("Invalid string\n");
    exit(1);
}

/* Grammar functions */
void S();
void L();
void Lprime();

/* S → ( L ) | a */
void S() {
    if (get() == '(') {
        advance();          // (
        L();
        if (get() != ')') error();
        advance();          // )
    }
    else if (get() == 'a') {
        advance();          // a
    }
    else {
        error();
    }
}

/* L → S L' */
void L() {
    S();
    Lprime();
}

/* L' → , S L' | ε */
void Lprime() {
    while (get() == ',') {
        advance();          // ,
        S();
    }
}

int main() {
    printf("Enter string: ");
    scanf("%s", input);

    S();

    if (get() == '\0')
        printf("Valid string\n");
    else
        printf("Invalid string\n");

    return 0;
}
```

---

# ✔ Valid Examples

```
a
(a)
(a,a)
((a),a)
(a,(a,a))
```

# ❌ Invalid Examples

```
()
(,)
(a,
a)
((a),)
```
